{
  "answer": "**Viṣṇu Smṛti, Chapter 44**, provides this exact list (among others) of stolen items and the animal rebirths they cause, as consequences for thieves after suffering in hells.[^1]\n\nThe relevant verses (Vi_44.14–29) are:\n\n> A grain-thief becomes a **rat**. // Vi_44.14 //  \n> A stealer of **bronze** becomes a **swan**. // Vi_44.15 //  \n> ...  \n> Of **milk**, a **crow**. // Vi_44.18 //  \n> Of **clarified butter [ghee]** [ichneumon/**mongoose**]. // Vi_44.20 // (\"Ichneumon\" is a mongoose.)  \n> Of **meat**, a **vulture**. // Vi_44.21 //  \n> ...  \n> Of **salt**, a **cricket**. // Vi_44.24 //  \n> ...  \n> **Stealing silk**, one becomes a **partridge**. // Vi_44.26 //  \n> ...  \n> A **cow**, an **iguana**. // Vi_44.29 //\n\n(Note: \"Clarified butter\" is *ghee*; the full chapter lists ~30 such pairs.)\n\n**Manusmṛti, Chapter 12**, supplies a near-identical list in verses 62–64 (with minor variants like \"savory liquid\" for juice/dog).[^2]\n\n> Having stolen **grain**, one becomes a **rat**; **bronze**, a **swan**; ... **milk**, a **crow**; ... **ghee**, a **mongoose**. // Mn_12.62 //  \n> **Meat**, a **vulture**; ... **salt**, a **cricket**; ... // Mn_12.63 //  \n> Having stolen **silk**, one becomes a **partridge**; ... a **cow**, an **iguana**; ... // Mn_12.64 //\n\nThese texts draw from shared Smṛti traditions on karma and rebirth.\n\n[^1]: Viṣṇu Smṛti, *Chapter 44*, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/44/translation/#p-10f0fc#p-3e2aab#p-a135b8#p-0bb922#p-6e9baf#p-70946b#p-6d177e#p-079180).\n\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, *Chapter 12*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/12/translation/#p-074f6e).",
